Rating: 4
I cooked this dish per the recipe but added 1/2 cup cabernet. I braised it in a 7 qt french oven at 300 for 2 1/2 hours. at the last half hour I added a cup of beef broth and 8 oz of couscous. It was extremely tender with a fantastic flavor. The lab loved the bone.

Rating: 3
Somewhere I got spoiled with the tenderest lambshanks that appeared on a plate covered in the richest, red wine, sweet, syrupy glaze. This is not them, but they're still good.

Rating: 4
I have never cooked lamb shanks prior to this evening. I stuck to the recipe for the most part although, I spent more time browning the meat and more time cooking the veggies. I used only about a cup and a half of chicken broth, no beef broth, and subbed with (Merlot)&(chardonnay) wine, and (some beer once I realized my liquid mostly cooked off). I cooked the shanks a bit longer and I added two dried chipotles, a bay leaf, teaspoon-or more curry powder, 1/2 teaspoon Chile powder. I served it with mashed potatoes. Also, a rough version of creamed spinach found on this site using frozen spinach was a very nice side.

